Milestone 3 Write-Up  
Spencer Reith and Jackson Easley

**Task 1: Deploy a functional Cloud environment for your example organization**

Overview  
We began by analyzing our plan detailed in Milestone 2, Task 2\. Specifics about our plan can be found under the ‘Wiki – Milestone 2 – Task 2’ section. An abbreviated version of our plan is listed below:

1. Set up the campaign environment  
2. Set up the attacker’s environment  
3. Launch an attack against the unprotected campaign  
4. Upgrade the campaign environment to increase security  
5. Launch an attack against the upgraded campaign

For this Milestone, we were required to deploy a functional cloud environment, and ensure its functionality. So, we implemented steps 1 and 2 of the aforementioned plan. Steps 3, 4, and 5, involve launching attacks, and fit under the umbrella of Milestone 4\.

Per Milestone 2 Task 2, we’ve listed an abbreviated version of subtasks required by our plan to deploy our cloud environment.

1\. Campaign Environment Setup

* Launch a RedHat instance to hold campaign website  
* Allow HTTP and HTTPS traffic, and SSH traffic from anywhere. This will change in step 4\.  
* Create a basic campaign website in HTML  
  * We will have 6 separate pages  
    * Each of the five departments will have a page  
    * There will be a 6th page, including a form from which the users can ‘donate’ to the campaign  
    * This form will be run by a PHP Script  
* Store data in MySQL database  
* Archive data in an S3 Storage block to optimize efficiency

2\. Attacker Environment Setup

* Create a windows server, from where we will launch attacks  
* RDP into our virtual windows desktop

Changes Made to Our Plan

As we began implementing our environment, we noticed some portions of the plan were inefficient or could be upgraded.

1. We planned to have a separate ‘donations’ page. Instead, we incorporated the donations feature on our ‘Finance’ page.  
2. We decided that there was no real need to archive data. The focus of our project is preventing DDoS attacks, not protection of data. By focusing in on this niche (while still covering lots of depth and breadth), we were able to gain a better understanding of the material without spreading ourselves too thin.  
3. We decided to have our attacker use a Redhat instance, instead of a windows instance. The software we wanted to use to simulate a DDoS attack was better suited for linux, so we decided that Redhat was a good alternative to windows.  
4. We opted to use nmap, instead of HPing3 to send our packets. Unfortunately HPing costs money and would need to be payed for outside of our AWS accounts. However, we were able to successfully install nmap, and it contains similar features that (with some research and creativity) will allow us to flood our server with packets.
